{comment: The whole song is one loop — every section plays the progression below; the words ride it.}

{start_of_verse: Progression — every section}
[G]      [C]      [D7]      [D7]      [G]
{end_of_verse}

{comment: 1 · Instrumental playthrough — repeats off: section 2, section 2, close on section 1.}

{comment: 2 · From the top, same progression, now sung:}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[G]From the great Atlantic Ocean to the [C]wide Pacific shore,
[D7]To the green old flow'ring mountains, to the [G]ice-bound Labrador,
[G]She's long and tall and handsome and [C]known quite well to all,
[D7]She's the modern combination called the [G]Wabash Cannonball.
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_chorus}
[G]So listen to the jingle, the [C]jumble and the roar,
As she [D7]glides along the woodlands, through the hills and by the [G]shore,
[G]Hear the mighty rush of the engine, and the [C]lonesome hoboes squall,
While [D7]riding through the jungle on the [G]Wabash Cannonball.
{end_of_chorus}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
[G]She came in from Birmingham on a [C]cold and frosty day,
As she [D7]rolled into the station, you could hear the [G]people say,
"There's a [G]gal out there from Tennessee, she's [C]long, boy, and tall,
[D7]She's the modern combination called the [G]Wabash Cannonball."
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_chorus}
[G]So listen to the jingle, the [C]jumble and the roar,
As she [D7]glides along the woodlands, through the hills and by the [G]shore,
[G]Hear the mighty rush of the engine, and the [C]lonesome hoboes squall,
While [D7]riding through the jungle on the [G]Wabash Cannonball.
{end_of_chorus}

{comment: 3 · Instrumental close — section 3 as written, then end the whole song on section 2.}
